Here is a thorough survey of the optional-scalar and optional-index idioms in the TigerBeetle codebase, drawn from representative files across [`src/vsr/`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr), [`src/lsm/`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm), [`src/vsr/client.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/client.zig), and [`src/stdx/stdx.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/stdx.zig).

---

## 1. `?T = null` as the canonical "not-yet-set" field

TigerBeetle uses `?T = null` fields pervasively to represent **lifecycle state** — a field that is absent until some async event fires and then permanently set, or a "work slot" that is null when idle and non-null when occupied. There is no use of sentinel integers (`0xFF`, `-1`, etc.) for this purpose.

### Phase/lifecycle fields

In [`src/vsr/client.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/client.zig#L91-L99), both `batch_size_limit` and `request_inflight` follow this pattern:

```zig
/// Set by the `register`'s reply.
batch_size_limit: ?u32 = null,

/// Tracks a currently processing request submitted by `register()` or `raw_request()`.
request_inflight: ?Request = null,
```

`batch_size_limit` starts `null`, is set exactly once when the server sends a `RegisterResult`, and is never null again. `request_inflight` oscillates null/non-null to represent the single-flight slot.

The idiom at the receive site is to `assert` the previous state, then assign:

```zig
// Before registering:
assert(self.batch_size_limit == null);

// After receiving register reply:
self.batch_size_limit = result.batch_size_limit;
```

And to use `.?` (force-unwrap) only when the invariant is known, always accompanied by an earlier `assert`:

```zig
assert(events.len <= self.batch_size_limit.?);
```

### Copy-index cursor (`?u8`)

In [`src/vsr/superblock.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/superblock.zig#L664-L670), the in-progress write copy index is expressed as `?u8`:

```zig
pub const Context = struct {
    read_threshold: ?Quorums.Threshold = null,
    copy: ?u8 = null,                                // ← the index
    vsr_state: ?SuperBlockHeader.VSRState = null,
    view_headers: ?vsr.Headers.ViewChangeArray = null,
    repairs: ?Quorums.RepairIterator = null,
};
```

The field starts null, is set to `0` to begin iterating over superblock copies, incremented on each callback, and reset to `null` when the write loop completes:

```zig
context.copy = 0;                       // start loop
// ...
assert(context.copy.? < constants.superblock_copies);
superblock.staging.copy = context.copy.?;
// ...
if (copy + 1 == constants.superblock_copies) {
    context.copy = null;                // done; reset
    superblock.read_working(context, .verify);
} else {
    context.copy = copy + 1;            // advance
    superblock.write_header(context);
}
```

The pattern:
- Set to `null` as the "idle" marker.
- Force-unwrap with `.?` only inside guarded branches or preceded by `assert(… != null)`.
- Reset to `null` again to signal completion/idle.

### Array of optional slots (`[N]?u8`)

[`src/vsr/superblock_quorums.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/superblock_quorums.zig#L28) uses `[N]?u8 = @splat(null)` to represent a sparse slot array — each slot is either occupied with a copy number or absent:

```zig
/// An integer value indicates the copy index found in the corresponding slot.
/// A `null` value indicates that the copy is invalid or not a member of the working quorum.
slots: [options.superblock_copies]?u8 = @splat(null),
```

Iteration uses `if (slot) |copy|` to consume the optional:

```zig
for (iterator.slots) |slot| {
    if (slot) |copy| {
        if (copies_any.is_set(copy)) copies_duplicate.set(copy);
        copies_any.set(copy);
    }
}
```

And chained `orelse` for priority selection:

```zig
const repair = a orelse b orelse c orelse {
    for (iterator.slots) |slot| assert(slot != null);
    return null;
};
```

